04464nam a22005535i 9780226701714DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267017147 a10.7208/97802267017142doi  a(DE-B1597)524043  a(OCoLC)749264975  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aGN33.R25 2011 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a301a3011 aRabinow, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Accompaniment :bAssembling the Contemporary /cPaul Rabinow. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Think About It -- tPart One. Men of Knowledge in Search of Redemption or Salvation -- t1. Humanism as Nihilism: The Bracketing of Truth and Seriousness in American Cultural Anthropology -- t2. Chicken or Glass: Between Clifford Geertz and Paul Hyman -- t3. Foucault’s Untimely Struggle: Toward a Form of Spirituality -- t4. Michel Foucault: A Philosopher’s Morality? Toward a Bios Technika -- tPart Two. In Search of a Contemporary Anthropology -- t5. Collaboration, Concepts, and Assemblages -- t6. Venues: The Labinar and the Anthropology of the Contemporary Research Collaboratory -- t7. An Experiment in Discordancy: Reflections on Familiarity, Trust, and Confidence in Synthetic Biology -- t8. Why There Is No Contemporary Bioscience, Only a Modern One -- t9. The Accompaniment: On the Contemporary and the Untimely -- tConclusion: The Demands of the Day: An Untimely Accompaniment -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Names and Titles0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this culmination of his search for anthropological concepts and practices appropriate to the twenty-first century, Paul Rabinow contends that to make sense of the contemporary anthropologists must invent new forms of inquiry. He begins with an extended rumination on what he gained from two of his formative mentors: Michel Foucault and Clifford Geertz. Reflecting on their lives as teachers and thinkers, as well as human beings, he poses questions about their critical limitations, unfulfilled hopes, and the lessons he learned from and with them. This spirit of collaboration animates The Accompaniment, as Rabinow assesses the last ten years of his career, largely spent engaging in a series of intensive experiments in collaborative research and often focused on cutting-edge work in synthetic biology. He candidly details the successes and failures of shifting his teaching practice away from individual projects, placing greater emphasis on participation over observation in research, and designing and using websites as a venue for collaboration. Analyzing these endeavors alongside his efforts to apply an anthropological lens to the natural sciences, Rabinow lays the foundation for an ethically grounded anthropology ready and able to face the challenges of our contemporary world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnthropologyxUnited States. 0aAnthropologyzUnited States. 0aAnthropology. 0aInterdisciplinary researchxUnited States. 0aInterdisciplinary researchzUnited States. 0aInterdisciplinary research. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226701714423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226701714.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles